answers.body_markdown:
To test that if all work well with default implementation I recommend you to provide a `UserDetailsService` bean something like this:
It is a default one as example according to [documentation][1]

      @Bean
      public InMemoryUserDetailsManager users() {
        return new InMemoryUserDetailsManager(
            User.withUsername(&quot;myname&quot;)
                .password(passwordEncoder().encode(&quot;password&quot;))
                .authorities(&quot;read&quot;)
                .build()
        );
      }
    
      @Bean
      public PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder() {
        return new BCryptPasswordEncoder();
      }

Some details about `filterChain` also you should have something like this:

    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        http
                .authorizeHttpRequests((authz) -&gt; authz
                        .anyRequest().authenticated()
                )
                .httpBasic(withDefaults());
                .formLogin(Customizer.withDefaults())
        return http.build();

}

NOW you can to try to login with `myname` as login and `password` as password. Something like this.


But in controller layer you also have a `registration` here i think you should analyze/read/try with documentation this one implementation. Here I just can add some good references aka **HOW TO**

[JDBC Authentication][2]

[Storage Mechanisms][3]


  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-security/reference/servlet/authentication/passwords/in-memory.html
  [2]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-security/reference/servlet/authentication/index.html
  [3]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-security/reference/servlet/authentication/passwords/storage.html

