I don&#39;t think the **Scanner#useDelimiter()** is really what you want to use for this sort of thing. You are expecting the User to enter in vector data then you want to validate that entry to ensure it is in the correct format. If it isn&#39;t then provide a relatively detailed reason why it&#39;s not valid. 

To be honest, entry mistakes will always be done especially if it involves more that one character but, the User will have far greater success with his/her entries if....they know exactly what they are expected to enter. Throw the User a bone and let them know before you toss out a prompt like: `&quot;Please enter your vector&quot;`. You would find that if an entry error is made, then just an `Invalid Entry! (34.4, 55.1&gt;) - Try again...` message should pretty much suffice. The User can see exactly where the problem is and then make a correct attempt. 

To validate the a User&#39;s entry, the [String#matches()](https://www.tutorialspoint.com/java/java_string_matches.htm) method can be used along with a [Regular Expression](https://www.vogella.com/tutorials/JavaRegularExpressions/article.html) (regex), for *example*:

```
String commandLine = &quot;&quot;;
while (commandLine.isEmpty()) {
    System.out.print(&quot;Please enter your vector data (q to quit): -&gt; &quot;);
    commandLine = userInputScanner.nextLine().trim();

    /* Validate Entry - If the entry does NOT match the regex 
       then inform User and allow him/her to try again.    */
    if (!commandLine.matches(&quot;^(\\&lt;(-?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?),\\s?(-?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?)\\&gt;)$&quot;)) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Invalid Vector Entry Supplied! (&quot; + commandLine + &quot;) - Try again...&quot; );
        commandLine = &quot;&quot;;  // Empty `commandLine` to ensure re-loop.
    }
}
VectorCoordinate vc = VectorCalculator.parseVectorString(commandLine);
```

**What does the regex passed to the [String#matches()](https://www.tutorialspoint.com/java/java_string_matches.htm) method mean?**
 

 - `^` Asserts position at start of the String;
 - `\\&lt;` The first literal character must be the Less-Than (&lt;) character;
 - `(-?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?)` Next must be a string representation of a signed
   or unsigned Integer or Floating Point value;
 - `,` The supplied numerical value must be followed by a comma (,);
 - `\\s?` The comma may or may not be followed by a single white-space;
 - `(-?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?)` The comma (or comma + white-space) must be followed by a string
   representation of a signed or unsigned Integer or Floating Point
   value;
 - `\\&gt;` The last literal character must be the Greater-Than (&gt;)
   character;
 - `$` Asserts position at the end of the String.

