where $oldprice and $newprice are parameters to the stylesheet.

I&#39;ve used XSLT 3.0 syntax here for brevity but if you prefer to use an XSLT 1.0 processor it&#39;s perfectly feasible, just a bit more verbose.

Using XSLT for this problem in Java is possible but gets awkward if your replacements differ for various input values. Using XPath and DOM-API is much easier.

Given an input XML document like this:
```
&lt;container&gt;
	&lt;trade_qty&gt;&lt;![CDATA[123]]&gt;&lt;/trade_qty&gt;
	&lt;trade_qty&gt;&lt;![CDATA[234]]&gt;&lt;/trade_qty&gt;
	&lt;fixed_price&gt;&lt;![CDATA[345.67]]&gt;&lt;/fixed_price&gt;
	&lt;fixed_price&gt;&lt;![CDATA[456.78]]&gt;&lt;/fixed_price&gt;
&lt;/container&gt;
```

```
@Test
void testReplace() throws Exception {
    // Just for reading the source XML document
    var r = new DOMResult();
    try(InputStream is = getClass().getResourceAsStream(&quot;/replace.xml&quot;)) {
        TransformerFactory.newInstance().newTransformer().transform(new StreamSource(is), r);
    }
    
    Node doc = r.getNode(); // This is your XML document as a DOM-Node
    
    // REPLACEMENT BEGIN
