answers.body_markdown:
I found a solution which work for the moment.

In the pom.xml of myLibrary, I had this:

```
    &lt;properties&gt;
        &lt;maven.compiler.source&gt;1.8&lt;/maven.compiler.source&gt;
        &lt;maven.compiler.target&gt;1.8&lt;/maven.compiler.target&gt;
        &lt;project.build.sourceEncoding&gt;UTF-8&lt;/project.build.sourceEncoding&gt;
        &lt;revision&gt;${revision}&lt;/revision&gt;
[...]
    &lt;/properties&gt;
```

The solution was to replace the variable ${revision} with a hardcoded value:

```
    &lt;properties&gt;
        &lt;maven.compiler.source&gt;1.8&lt;/maven.compiler.source&gt;
        &lt;maven.compiler.target&gt;1.8&lt;/maven.compiler.target&gt;
        &lt;project.build.sourceEncoding&gt;UTF-8&lt;/project.build.sourceEncoding&gt;
        &lt;revision&gt;1.0&lt;/revision&gt;
[...]
    &lt;/properties&gt;
```

And now it seems it works.

You need to register the `MultiPartFeature` in your web.xml. You can simply add an `&lt;init-param&gt;` to the Jersey servlet

    &lt;init-param&gt;
        &lt;param-name&gt;jersey.config.server.provider.classnames&lt;/param-name&gt;
        &lt;param-value&gt;org.glassfish.jersey.media.multipart.MultiPartFeature&lt;/param-value&gt;
    &lt;/init-param&gt;

* See explanation of problem [here](https://stackoverflow.com/a/29406656/2587435)

* See other configuring options [here](https://stackoverflow.com/a/29534950/2587435)

